Since $z^{1997} - 1 = 0,$ $z^{1997} = 1.$  This means that $z$ is a 1997th root of unity.  The 1997th roots of unity are of the form
\[e^{2 \pi i k/1997},\]where $0 \le k \le 1996.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  return (cos(2*pi*t),sin(2*pi*t));
}

path foo = moo(0);
real t;

for (t = 1/1997; t <= 1; t = t + 1/1997) {
  foo = foo--moo(t);
}

draw(foo,red);
draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0));
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2));

dot((1,0));
[/asy]

Geometrically, these roots lie on the unit circle in the complex plane, evenly spaced.  We can think of these roots as the vertices of a regular 1997-gon.

